Question

A canoe travels 2.4 m/s relative to the water. A river, heading east, flows at 2.8 m/s. The canoe points at a direction 145° counterclockwise from east.


Find the canoe’s total speed, in m/s, and direction of travel, as degrees counterclockwise from east.

  • Speed = ##ANSWER1##
  • Direction = ##ANSWER2##

Answerlist

  • 1.4 m/s
  • 1.5 m/s
  • 1.6 m/s
  • 1.7 m/s
  • 1.8 m/s
  • 1.9 m/s
  • 54°
  • 55°
  • 56°
  • 57°
  • 58°
  • 59°

Solution

First, find the rectangular coordinates of each velocity vector. The two formulas:

\[x~=~r\cdot\cos(\theta)\] \[y~=~r\cdot\sin(\theta)\]

We will use \(\vec{v}_1\) for the canoe’s velocity relative to water. It is shown below with approximate rectangular coordinates (found from formulas above, using \(r=2.4\) and \(\theta=145\)°).

\[\vec{v}_1 = (-1.966,1.377)\]

We will use \(\vec{v}_2\) for the river’s velocity vector. Since the river flows directly east, all of its speed is in the positive horizontal direction.

\[\vec{v}_2 = (2.800,0.000)\]

Now, add the corresponding components to find \(\vec{v}_3\), the velocity of the canoe relative to the ground.

\[\vec{v}_3 = (0.834,1.377)\]

Lastly, we need to find the polar coordinates. The formulas are given below. Notice, I am using the two-argument arctangent function.

\[r~=~\sqrt{x^2+y^2}\] \[\theta~=~\arctan(y,x)\]

So,

\[r=\sqrt{(0.834)^2+(1.377)^2}~=~1.609533\]

\[\theta=\arctan(1.377,0.834)~=~58.7894487°\]

This can be visualized.
